=David Prager Branner=
Lexicographer of Chinese, and scholar of historical phonology, dialectology (Min and Hakka) with broad interest in computer science

[[@http://branner.americanorientalsociety.org/|Official Website]] 


Inventor of a Transcription System for Teaching Medieval Chinese applied in the [[@http://yintong.americanorientalsociety.org/public/|Yīntōng 音通 database]].

==Literature==
===Dissertation===
* Wann'an dialects of Longyan County, Fukien, and their place within the Miin branch of Chinese. Ph.D., University of Washington, 1997 , 400 pages
===Monographs===
* The Chinese rime tables : linguistic philosophy and historical-comparative phonology. Amsterdam [u.a.] : Benjamins, 2006
* Problems in comparative Chinese dialectology : the classification of Miin and Hakka. Branner, David Prager. - Berlin : Mouton de Gruyter, 2000 
===Articles===
* A Neutral Transcription System for Teaching Medieval Chinese. T‘ang Studies 17 (1999) [[@http://americanorientalsociety.org/yintong/public/Branner_MedievalSpelling.pdf|pdf]] 
* “Phonology in the Chinese Script and its Relationship to Early Chinese Literacy.”. In Li Feng and David Prager Branner, eds., Writing and Literacy in Early China (Seattle: University of Washington Press, 2011), 85–137 [[http://branner.americanorientalsociety.org/dpb/publications/Branner_Phonology_in_Chinese_Script_final_20110627.pdf|pdf]] 
* “The Suí-Táng Tradition of Fǎnqiè Phonology.” Article 5 of the Geschichte der Sprachwissenschaften — History of the Language Sciences — Histoire des sciences du language — an International Handbook on the Evolution of the Study of Language from the Beginnings to the Present, edited by Sylvain Auroux, Konrad Koerner, Hans-Josef Niederehe, and Kees Versteegh. Berlin: De Gruyter, 2000. Pp. 36-46.
*  “The Rime-table System of Formal Chinese Phonology.” Article 6 of the Geschichte der Sprachwissenschaften — History of the Language Sciences — Histoire des sciences du language — an International Handbook on the Evolution of the Study of Language from the Beginnings to the Present, edited by Sylvain Auroux, Konrad Koerner, Hans-Josef Niederehe, and Kees Versteegh. Berlin: De Gruyter, 2000. Pp. 46-55. 